<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"  xml:id="chap_preliminaries">
  <title>Preliminaries</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Here are some Greek roots:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{kryptos}, <m>\kappa\rho\upsilon\pi\tau o\sigma</m></title>
          <p>
            secret, hidden <idx><h>kryptos [<m>\kappa\rho\upsilon\pi\tau o\sigma</m>, Greek root]</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{logos}, <m>\lambda\acute{o}\gamma o\sigma</m></title>
          <p>
            word, study,
            speech <idx><h>logos [<m>\lambda\acute{o}\gamma o\sigma</m>, Greek root]</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{graph}, <m>\gamma\rho\acute{\alpha}\phi\omega</m></title>
          <p>
            write, written <idx><h>graph [<m>\gamma\rho\acute{\alpha}\phi\omega</m>, Greek root]</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{analysis}, <m>\alpha\nu\acute{\alpha}\lambda\upsilon\eta</m></title>
          <p>
            analysis <idx><h>analysis [<m>\alpha\nu\acute{\alpha}\lambda\upsilon\eta</m>, Greek root]</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      From these (and others), modern (technical) English gets the words
      <ul>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{cryptosystem}</title>
          <p>
            a set of algorithms for protecting secrets,
            for hiding information so that only the intended persons have access to it
              <idx><h>cryptosystem</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{cryptography}</title>
          <p>
            work done to make cryptosystems
              <idx><h>cryptography</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{cryptanalysis}</title>
          <p>
            work done to circumvent the protections of
              <idx><h>cryptanalysis</h></idx>
            cryptosystems <mdash/> to
            <q>crack</q>
            a cryptosystem
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>\textit{cryptology}</title>
          <p>
            the combination of cryptography and cryptanalysis,
            often abbreviated simply to {crypto
              <idx><h>crypto</h></idx>
            }.
              <idx><h>cryptology</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Beware that <em>cryptography</em> is widely
      (but inappropriately!)
      used as a synecdoche for <em>cryptology</em>.
      We will use these words more carefully,
      except when the differences between the words is not so important,
      in which case we will use the word <em>crypto
          <idx><h>crypto</h></idx>
      </em> as short for whichever of cryptology,
      cryptography, or cryptanalysis is most appropriate<fn>
      Note this use of
      <q>crypto</q>
      conflicts a little with a silly modern usage of that word as short for <em>cryptocurrency
          <idx><h>cryptocurrency</h></idx>
      </em>.
      We will return to that topic much later,
      when we talk about <em>blockchains
          <idx><h>blockchains</h></idx>
      </em>.
      </fn>
    </p>
  </introduction>
